Vice President Kamala Harris visited the headquarters of Applied Materials in Sunnyvale, California, to discuss the importance of public-private partnerships in driving innovation and maintaining global leadership for the United States. Harris, who has a personal connection to the scientific community through her mother, emphasized the need for collaboration and investment in the semiconductor industry, which she described as the foundation of 21st-century technology. She also highlighted the importance of strengthening the workforce by focusing on skills training and education. The Vice President commended the United States' historical role in semiconductor research and development and announced a $53 billion investment in semiconductor R&D and manufacturing. Harris expressed her excitement about the future and the potential for advancements in technology and the improvement of the human condition. The meeting concluded with a working session.